<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-498-857  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 498 857.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Oct 8 1990 v24 n41 p34(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Going on-line helps Connecticut manage environmental concerns. (OnSite)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Cusack, Sally.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Connecticut's Department of Environmental Protection implements anon-line Environmental Information System to help maintain thestate's clean air requirements.andP;  The system includes 30 remotesite detectors that report air quality data to the agency's DataGeneral Corp MV minicomputers.andP;  If the remote detectors sensealarming levels of certain pollutants, they will send reports tothe main computer, and the staff at the agency can determine whataction to take.andP;  The computer system uses specially writtensoftware from SAS Institute Inc of Cary, NC.andP;  The software fromSAS is integrated in such a way as to allow easy data merging forreport writing and complex data analysis.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   SAS Institute Inc. (products)Data General Corp. (products).andO;Ticker:    DGN.andO;Topic:     Case StudyEnvironmental protectionSystem SelectionGovernment AgencyOn-Line.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>